While both abortion and spousal violence are illegal, according to the report, improper abortion, along with pregnancy-related complications, results in over 6,000 maternal deaths each year in 
Myanmar. Nearly half these maternal deaths result from unsafe abortions. But the immediate negative impact of legal restrictions on safe abortion is magnified by poverty and other social factors that limit access to adequate health care, according to the report. Awzar Oo, Coordinator at Choice Network, a support group for the sexual and reproductive health rights of people in Myanmar, told IRIN access to legal abortions should start with education on family planning. “Most of all, we need increased access to free contraceptives, and we need to overturn the fear mongering surrounding safe abortions,” he said. 
Recently, there were cases of women committing suicide because of poor health related to abortion. According to the report, the introduction of Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances​ Tax Act for Burmese women stems from the West where “abortion was treated as a crime for decades” and “the criminalization of abortion was connected to the broader attack on women’s rights.” “But this provided fertile ground to medical authorities who wanted to control the practice of abortion ,” the UN say, adding that in Myanmar, spousal violence is also criminalized.
